obj_root_law_sections_1:
  sectionId (43937)
  sectionNo (1)
  orderNo 1
  title `Short title.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_1_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_1_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43937&sectionno=1&orderno=1&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_1_content:
  string
  line `This Act may be called the Indian Easements Act, 1882.`
  line
  line `Local extent.--It extends^1`
  line `to the territories respectively administered by the Governor of Madras`
  line `in Council and the Chief Commissioners of the Central Provinces and Coorg;`
  line
  line `Commencement.--and it shall come into force on the first day of July, 1882.`
  line
  line `STATE AMENDMENTS`
  line
  line Karnataka
  line
  line `Amendment of Central Act V of 1882.--In section 1 of the Indian Easements Act, 1882`
  line `(Central Act V of 1882) for the entry under the heading "Local extent", the following entry shall be`
  line `substituted, namely:--`
  line
  line `"It extends to the whole of the State of Karnataka".`
  line
  line `[Vide Karnataka Act 33 of 1978, s. 6].`
obj_root_law_sections_1_footnotes:
  string
  line `1. The Act was extended to--`
  line
  line `(1) Ajmer-Merwara by notification under s. 5 of the Scheduled Districts Act, 1874 (14 of 1874), see Gazette of India,`
  line `1897, Pt. II, p. 1413;`
  line
  line `(2) Bombay and the U.P. by Act 8 of 1891 and continued in force, with modifications, in the territory transferred to`
  line `Delhi State, see the Delhi Laws Act, 1915 (7 of 1915), s. 3 and the Third Schedule;`
  line
  line `(3) Whole of Madhya Pradesh by Madhya Pradesh Act 23 of 1958;`
  line
  line `(4) Punjab by Punjab Act 29 of 1961;`
  line
  line `(5) Kerala by Kerala Act 5 of 1962;`
  line
  line `(6) Pondicherry by Act 26 of 1968, s. 3 and Schedule.`
  line
  line `(7) Extended to the Union territory of Jammu and Kashmir and Union territory of Ladakh by Act 34 of 2019 s. 95 and`
  line `the Fifth Schedule (w.e.f. 31-10- 2019).`
  line
  line `The Act has been repealed in its application to Bellary District by Mysore Act 14 of 1955.`
obj_root_law_sections_2:
  sectionId (43938)
  sectionNo (2)
  orderNo 2
  title Savings.
  content obj_root_law_sections_2_content
  footnotes `1. Subs. by the A.O. 1950, for "Crown".`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43938&sectionno=2&orderno=2&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_2_content:
  string
  line `Nothing herein contained shall be deemed to affect any law not hereby expressly`
  line `repealed; or to derogate from--`
  line
  line `(a) any right of the ^1[Government] to regulate the collection, retention and distribution of the`
  line `water of rivers and streams flowing in natural channels, and of natural lakes and ponds, or of the`
  line `water flowing, collected, retained or distributed in or by any channel or other work constructed at`
  line `the public expense for irrigation;`
  line
  line `(b) any customary or other right (not being a license) in or over immovable property which the`
  line `Government, the public or any person may possess irrespective of other immovable property; or`
  line
  line `(c) any right acquired, or arising out of a relation created, before this Act comes into force.`
obj_root_law_sections_3:
  sectionId (43939)
  sectionNo (3)
  orderNo 3
  title `Construction of certain references to Act 15 of 1877 and Act 9 of 1871.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_3_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43939&sectionno=3&orderno=3&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_3_content:
  string
  line `^1[3. Construction of certain references to Act 15 of 1877 and Act 9 of 1871.--All references in`
  line `any Act or Regulation to sections 26 and 27 of the Indian Limitation Act, 1877^2 or to sections 27 and`
  line `28 of Act No. 9 of 1871^3`
  line `shall, in the territories to which this Act extends, be read as made to sections`
  line `15 and 16 of this Act.]`
obj_root_law_sections_3_footnotes:
  string
  line `1. Subs. by Act 10 of 1914, s. 2 and the First Schedule, for s. 3.`
  line
  line `2. See now the Limitation Act, 1963 (36 of 1963).`
  line
  line `3. Rep. by Act 15 of 1877.`
obj_root_law_sections_4:
  sectionId (43940)
  sectionNo (4)
  orderNo 4
  title `"Easement" defined.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_4_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43940&sectionno=4&orderno=4&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_4_content:
  string
  line `An easement is a right which the owner or occupier of certain`
  line `land possesses, as such, for the beneficial enjoyment of that land, to do and continue to do`
  line `something, or to prevent and continue to prevent something being done, in or upon, or in respect of,`
  line `certain other land not his own.`
  line
  line `Dominant and servient heritages and owners.--The land for the beneficial enjoyment of which`
  line `the right exists is called the dominant heritage, and the owner or occupier thereof the dominant owner; the land on which the liability is imposed is called the servient heritage, and the owner or occupier`
  line `thereof the servient owner.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--In the first and second clauses of this section, the expression "land" includes also`
  line `things permanently attached to the earth; the expression "beneficial enjoyment includes also possible`
  line `convenience, remote advantage, and even a mere amenity; and the expression "to do something"`
  line `includes removal and appropriation by the dominant owner, for the beneficial enjoyment of the`
  line `dominant heritage, of any part of the soil of the servient heritage or anything growing or subsisting`
  line thereon.
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A, as the owner of a certain house, has a right of way thither over his neighbour B's land for purposes`
  line `connected with the beneficial enjoyment of the house. This is an easement.`
  line
  line `(b) A, as the owner of a certain house, has the right to go on his neighbour B's land, and to take water for the`
  line `purposes of his household out of a spring therein. This is an easement.`
  line
  line `(c) A, as the owner of a certain house, has the right to conduct water from B's stream to supply the fountains`
  line `in the garden attached to the house. This is an easement.`
  line
  line `(d) A, as the owner of a certain house and farm, has the right to graze a certain number of his own cattle on`
  line `B's field, or to take, for the purpose of being used in the house, by himself, his family, guests, lodgers and`
  line `servants, water or fish out of C's tank, or timber out of D's wood, or to use, for the purpose of manuring his`
  line `land, the leaves which have fallen from the trees on E's land. These are easements.`
  line
  line `(e) A dedicates to the public the right to occupy the surface of certain land for the purpose of passing and`
  line `re-passing. This right is not an easement.`
  line
  line `(f) A is bound to cleanse a water course running through his land and keep it free from obstruction for the`
  line `benefit of B, a lower riparian owner. This is not an easement.`
obj_root_law_sections_4_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_5:
  sectionId (43941)
  sectionNo (5)
  orderNo 5
  title `Continuous and discontinuous, apparent and non-apparent, easements.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_5_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43941&sectionno=5&orderno=5&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_5_content:
  string
  line `Easements are`
  line `either continuous or discontinuous, apparent or non-apparent.`
  line
  line `A continuous easement is one whose enjoyment is, or may be, continual without the act of man.`
  line
  line `A discontinuous easement is one that needs the act of man for its enjoyment.`
  line `An apparent easement is one the existence of which is shown by some permanent sign which, upon`
  line `careful inspection by a competent person, would be visible to him.`
  line
  line `A non-apparent easement is one that has no such sign.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A right annexed to B’s house to receive light by the windows without obstruction by his neighbour A.`
  line
  line `This is a continuous easement.`
  line
  line `(b) A right of way annexed to A’s house over B’s land. This is a discontinuous easement.`
  line
  line `(c) Rights annexed to A’s land to lead water thither across B’s land by an aqueduct and to draw off water`
  line `thence by a drain. The drain would be discovered upon careful inspection by a person conversant with such`
  line `matters. These are apparent easements.`
  line
  line `(d) A right annexed to A’s house to prevent B from building on his own land. This is a non-apparent`
  line easement.
obj_root_law_sections_5_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_6:
  sectionId (43942)
  sectionNo (6)
  orderNo 6
  title `Easement for limited time or on condition.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_6_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43942&sectionno=6&orderno=6&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_6_content:
  string
  line `An easement may be permanent, or for a term of`
  line `years or other limited period, or subject to periodical interruption, or exercisable only at a certain`
  line `place or at certain times, or between certain hours, or for a particular purpose, or on`
  line `condition that it shall commence or become void or voidable on the happening of a specified event or the`
  line `performance or non-performance of a specified act.`
obj_root_law_sections_6_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_7:
  sectionId (43943)
  sectionNo (7)
  orderNo 7
  title `Easements restrictive of certain rights.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_7_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43943&sectionno=7&orderno=7&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_7_content:
  string
  line `Easements are restrictions of one or other of the`
  line `following rights (namely):--`
  line
  line `(a) Exclusive right to enjoy.--The exclusive right of every owner of immovable property (subject`
  line `to any law for the time being in force) to enjoy and dispose of the same and all products thereof and`
  line `accessions thereto.`
  line
  line `(b) Rights to advantages arising from situation.--The right of every owner of immovable`
  line `property (subject to any law for the time being in force) to enjoy without disturbance try another the`
  line `natural advantages arising from its situation.`
  line
  line `Illustrations of the rights above referred to`
  line
  line `(a) The exclusive right of every owner of land in a town to build on such land, subject to any municipal law for the`
  line `time being in force.`
  line
  line `(b) The right of every owner of land that the air passing thereto shall not be unreasonably polluted by other`
  line persons.
  line
  line `(c) The right of every owner of a house that his physical comfort shall not be interfered with materially and`
  line `unreasonably by noise or vibration caused by any other person.`
  line
  line `(d) The right of every owner of land to so much light and air as pass vertically thereto.`
  line
  line `(e) The right of every owner of land that such land, in its natural condition, shall have the support naturally`
  line `rendered by the subjacent and adjacent soil of another person.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--Land is in its natural condition when it is not excavated and not subjected to artificial pressure; and`
  line `the "subjacent and adjacent soil" mentioned in this illustration means such soil only as in its natural condition would`
  line `support the dominant heritage in its natural condition.`
  line
  line `(f) The right of every owner of land that, within his own limits, the water which naturally passes or percolates by,`
  line `over or through his land shall not, before so passing or percolating, be unreasonably polluted by other persons.`
  line
  line `(g) The right of every owner of land to collect and dispose within his own limits of all water under the land which`
  line `does not pass in a defined channel and all water on its surface which does not pass in a defined channel.`
  line
  line `(h) The right of every owner of land that the water of every natural stream which passes by, through or over his`
  line `land in a defined natural channel shall be allowed by other persons to flow within such owner's limits without`
  line `interruption and without material alteration in quantity, direction, force or temperature; the right of every owner of`
  line `land abutting on a natural lake or pond into or out of which a natural stream flows, that the water of such lake or pond`
  line `shall be allowed by other persons to remain within such owner's limits without material alteration in quantity or`
  line temperature.
  line
  line `(i) The right of every owner of upper land that water naturally rising in, or falling on, such land, and not passing in`
  line `defined channels, shall be allowed by the owner of adjacent lower land to run naturally thereto.`
  line
  line `(j) The right of every owner of land abutting on a natural stream, lake or pond to use and consume its water for`
  line `drinking, household purposes and watering his cattle and sheep; and the right of every such owner to use and consume`
  line `the water for irrigating such land and for the purposes of any manufactory situate thereon, provided that he does not`
  line `thereby cause material injury to other like owners.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--A natural stream is a stream, whether permanent or intermittent, tidal or tideless, on the surface of`
  line `land or underground, which flows by the operation of nature only and in a natural and known course.`
obj_root_law_sections_7_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_8:
  sectionId (43944)
  sectionNo (8)
  orderNo 8
  title `Who may impose easements.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_8_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43944&sectionno=8&orderno=8&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_8_content:
  string
  line `An easement may be imposed by any one in the circumstances,`
  line `and to the extent, in and to which he may transfer his interest in the heritage on which the liability is`
  line `to be imposed.`
  line
  line `(a) A is tenant of B's land under a lease for an unexpired term of twenty years, and has power to transfer his interest`
  line `under the lease. A may impose an easement on the land to continue during the time that the lease exists or for any shorter`
  line period.
  line
  line `(b) A is tenant for his life of certain land with remainder to B absolutely. A cannot, unless with B's consent,`
  line `impose an easement thereon which will continue after the determination of his life-interest.`
  line
  line `(c) A, B and C are co-owners of certain land. A cannot, without the consent of B and C, impose an easement on`
  line `the land or on any part thereof.`
  line
  line `(d) A and B are lessees of the same lessor, A of a field X for a term of five years, and B of a field Y for a term of`
  line `ten years. A's interest under his lease is transferable; B's is not. A may impose on X, in favour of B, a right of way`
  line `terminable with A’s lease.`
obj_root_law_sections_8_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_9:
  sectionId (43945)
  sectionNo (9)
  orderNo 9
  title `Servient owners.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_9_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43945&sectionno=9&orderno=9&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_9_content:
  string
  line `Subject to the provisions of section 8, a servient owner may impose on the`
  line `servient heritage any easement that does not lessen the utility of the existing easement. But he cannot,`
  line `without the consent of the dominant owner, impose an easement on the servient heritage which would`
  line `lessen such utility.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A has, in respect of his mill, a right to the uninterrupted flow thereto from sunrise to noon of the water of`
  line `B's stream. B may grant to C the right to divert the water of the stream from noon to sunset: Provided that A's`
  line `supply is not thereby diminished.`
  line
  line `(b) A has, in respect of his house, a right of way over B's land. B may grant to C, as the owner of a`
  line `neighbouring farm, the right to feed his cattle on the grass growing on the way: Provided that A's right of way is`
  line `not thereby obstructed.`
obj_root_law_sections_9_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_10:
  sectionId (43946)
  sectionNo (10)
  orderNo 10
  title `Lessor and mortgagor.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_10_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43946&sectionno=10&orderno=10&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_10_content:
  string
  line `Subject to the provisions of section 8, a lessor may impose, on the`
  line `property leased, any easement that does not derogate from the rights of the lessee as such, and a`
  line `mortgagor may impose, on the property mortgaged, any easement that does not render the security`
  line `insufficient. But a lessor or mortgagor cannot, without the consent of the lessee or mortgagee, impose`
  line `any other easement on such property, unless it be to take effect on the termination of the lease or the`
  line `redemption of the mortgage.`
  line
  line `Explanation.--A security is insufficient within the meaning of this section unless the value of the`
  line `mortgaged property exceeds by one-third, or, if consisting of buildings, exceeds by one-half, the`
  line `amount for the time being due on the mortgage.`
obj_root_law_sections_10_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_11:
  sectionId (43947)
  sectionNo (11)
  orderNo 11
  title Lessee.
  content obj_root_law_sections_11_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43947&sectionno=11&orderno=11&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_11_content:
  string
  line `No lessee or other person having a derivative interest may impose on the property`
  line `held by him as such an easement to take effect after the expiration of his own interest, or in derogation`
  line `of the right of the lessor or the superior proprietor.`
obj_root_law_sections_11_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_12:
  sectionId (43948)
  sectionNo (12)
  orderNo 12
  title `Who may acquire easements.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_12_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43948&sectionno=12&orderno=12&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_12_content:
  string
  line `An easement may be acquired by the owner of the`
  line `immovable property for the beneficial enjoyment of which the right is created or on his behalf, by any`
  line `person in possession of the same.`
  line
  line `One of two or more co-owners of immovable property may, as such, with or without the consent of`
  line `the other or others, acquire an easement for the beneficial enjoyment of such property.`
  line
  line `No lessee of immovable property can acquire, for the beneficial enjoyment of other immovable`
  line `property of his own, an easement in or over the property comprised in his lease.`
obj_root_law_sections_12_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_13:
  sectionId (43949)
  sectionNo (13)
  orderNo 13
  title `Easements of necessity and quasi easements.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_13_content
  footnotes `1. See now the Land Acquisition Act, 1894 (1 of 1894).`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43949&sectionno=13&orderno=13&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_13_content:
  string
  line `Where one person transfers or bequeaths`
  line `immovable property to another,--`
  line
  line `(a) if an easement in other immovable property of the transferor or testator is necessary for`
  line `enjoying the subject of the transfer or bequest, the transferee or legatee shall be entitled to such`
  line `easement; or`
  line
  line `(b) if such an easement is apparent and continuous and necessary for enjoying the said subject`
  line `as it was enjoyed when the transfer or bequest took effect, the transferee or legatee shall, unless a`
  line `different intention is expressed or necessarily implied, be entitled to such easement;`
  line
  line `(c) if an easement in the subject of the transfer or bequest is necessary for enjoying other immovable property of the transferor or testator, the transferor or the legal representative of`
  line `the testator shall be entitled to such easement; or`
  line
  line `(d) if such an easement is apparent and continuous and necessary for enjoying the said property`
  line `as it was enjoyed when the transfer or bequest took effect, the transferor, or the legal representative`
  line `of the testator, shall, unless a different intention is expressed or necessarily implied, be entitled to`
  line `such easement.`
  line
  line `Where a partition is made of the joint property of several persons,--`
  line
  line `(e) if an easement over the share of one of them is necessary for enjoying the share of another`
  line `of them, the latter shall be entitled to such easement, or`
  line
  line `(f) if such an easement is apparent and continuous and necessary for enjoying the share of the`
  line `latter as it was enjoyed when the partition took effect, he shall, unless a different intention is`
  line `expressed or necessarily implied, be entitled to such easement.`
  line
  line `The easements mentioned in this section, clauses (a), (c) and (e), are called easements of necessity.`
  line
  line `Where immovable property passes by operation of law, the persons from and to whom it so passes`
  line `are, for the purpose of this section, to be deemed, respectively, the transferor and transferee.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A sells B a field then used for agricultural purposes only. It is inaccessible except by passing over A's`
  line `adjoining land or by trespassing on the land of a stranger. B is entitled to a right of way, for agricultural`
  line `purposes only, over As adjoining land to the field sold.`
  line
  line `(b) A, the owner of two fields, sells one to B, and retains the other. The field retained was, at the date of the`
  line `sale, used for agricultural purposes only, and is inaccessible except by passing over the field sold to B. A is`
  line `entitled to a right of way, for agricultural purposes only, over B's field to the field retained.`
  line
  line `(c) A sells B a house with windows overlooking As land, which A retains. The light which passes over As`
  line `land to the windows is necessary for enjoying the house as it war enjoyed when the sale took effect. B is entitled`
  line `to the light, and A cannot afterwards obstruct it by building on his land.`
  line
  line `(d) A sells B a house with windows overlooking A's land. The light passing over As land to the windows is`
  line `necessary for enjoying the house as it was enjoyed when the sale took effect. Afterwards A sells the land to C.`
  line `Here C cannot obstruct the light by building on the land, for he takes it subject to the burdens to which it was`
  line `subject in As hands.`
  line
  line `(e) A is the owner of a house and adjoining land. The house has windows overlooking the land. A`
  line `simultaneously sells the house to B and the land to C. The light passing over the land is necessary for enjoying`
  line `the house as it was enjoyed when the sale took effect. Here A impliedly grants B a right to the light, and C takes`
  line `the land subject to the restriction that he may not build so as to obstruct such light.`
  line
  line `(f) A is the owner of a house and adjoining land. The house has windows over-looking the land. A, retaining`
  line `the house, sells the land to B, without expressly reserving any easement. The light passing over the land is`
  line `necessary for enjoying the house as it was enjoyed when the sale took effect. A is entitled to the light, and B`
  line `cannot build on the land so as to obstruct such light.`
  line
  line `(g) A, the owner of a house, sells B a factory built on adjoining land. B is entitled, as against A, to pollute`
  line `the air, when necessary, with smoke and vapours from the factory.`
  line
  line `(h) A, the owner of two adjoining houses, Y and Z, sells Y to B, and retains Z. B is entitled to the benefit of`
  line `all the gutters and drains common to the two houses and necessary for enjoying Y as it was enjoyed when the`
  line `sale took effect, and A is entitled to the benefit of all the gutters and drains common to the two houses and`
  line `necessary for enjoying Z as it was enjoyed when the sale took effect.`
  line
  line `(i) A, the owner of two adjoining buildings, sells one to B retaining the other. B is entitled to a right to lateral`
  line `support from As building, and A is entitled to a right to lateral support from B's building.`
  line
  line `(j) A, the owner of two adjoining buildings, sells one to B, and the other to C. C is entitled to lateral support`
  line `from B's building, and B is entitled to lateral support from C's building.`
  line
  line `(k) A grants lands to B for the purpose of building a house thereon. B is entitled to such amount of lateral`
  line `and subjacent support from As land as is necessary for the safety of the house.`
  line
  line `(l) Under the Land Aquisition Act, 1870^1`
  line `(10 of 1870), a Railway Company compulsorily acquires a portion`
  line `of B's land for the purpose of making a siding. The Company is entitled to such amount of lateral support from`
  line `B's adjoining land as is essential for the safety of the siding.`
  line
  line `(m) Owing to the partition of joint property, A becomes the owner of an upper room in a building, and B`
  line `becomes the owner of the portion of the building immediately beneath it. A is entitled to such amount of vertical`
  line `support from B's portion as is essential for the safety of the upper room.`
  line
  line `(n) A lets a house and grounds to B for a particular business. B has no access to them other than by crossing`
  line `A's land. B is entitled to a right of way over that land suitable to the business to be carried on by B in the house`
  line `and grounds.`
obj_root_law_sections_14:
  sectionId (43950)
  sectionNo (14)
  orderNo 14
  title `Direction of way of necessity.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_14_content
  footnotes `1. Subs. by Act 12 of 1891, s. 2 and the Second Schedule, for "right"`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43950&sectionno=14&orderno=14&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_14_content:
  string
  line `When ^1[a right] to a way of necessity is created under`
  line `section 13, the transferor, the legal representative of the testator, or the owner of the share over which`
  line `the right is exercised, as the case may be, is entitled to set out the way; but it must be reasonably`
  line `convenient for the dominant owner.`
  line
  line `When the person so entitled to set out the way refuses or neglects to do so, the dominant owner`
  line `may set it out.`
obj_root_law_sections_15:
  sectionId (43951)
  sectionNo (15)
  orderNo 15
  title `Acquisition by prescription.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_15_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43951&sectionno=15&orderno=15&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_15_content:
  string
  line `Where the access and use of light or air to and for any building`
  line `have been peaceably enjoyed therewith, as an easement, without interruption, and for twenty years,`
  line `and where support from one person's land or things affixed thereto has been peaceably received by`
  line `another person's land subjected to artificial pressure or by things affixed thereto as an easement,`
  line `without interruption, and for twenty years,`
  line
  line `and where a right of way or any other easement has been peaceably and openly enjoyed by any`
  line `person claiming title thereto, as an easement, and as of right, without interruption, and for twenty`
  line years,
  line
  line `the right to such access and use of light or air, support or other easement shall be absolute.`
  line
  line `Each of the said periods of twenty years shall be taken to be a period ending within two years next`
  line `before the institution of the suit wherein the claim to which such period relates is contested.`
  line
  line `Explanation I.--Nothing is an enjoyment within the meaning of this section when it has been had`
  line `in pursuance of an agreement with the owner or occupier of the property over which the right is`
  line `claimed, and it is apparent from the agreement that such right has not been granted as an easement, or,`
  line `if granted as an easement, that it has been granted for a limited period, or subject to a condition on the`
  line `fulfilment of which it is to cease.`
  line
  line `Explanation II.--Nothing is an interruption within the meaning of this section unless where there`
  line `is an actual cessation of the enjoyment by reason of an obstruction by the act of some person other`
  line `than the claimant, and unless such obstruction is submitted to or acquiesced in for one year after the`
  line `claimant has notice thereof and of the person making or authorising the same to be made.`
  line
  line `Explanation III.--Suspension of enjoyment in pursuance of a contract between the dominant and`
  line `servient owners is not an interruption within the meaning of this section.`
  line
  line `Explanation IV.--In the case of an easement to pollute water, the said period of twenty years`
  line `begins when the pollution first prejudices perceptibly the servient heritage.`
  line
  line `When the property over which a right is claimed under this section belongs to ^1[Government] this`
  line `section shall be read as if, for the words "twenty years", the words"`
  line `^2[thirty years]" were substituted.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A suit is brought in 1883 for obstructing a right of way. The defendant admits the obstruction,`
  line `but denies the right of way. The plaintiff proves that the right was peaceably and openly enjoyed by`
  line `him, claiming title thereto as an easement and as of right, without interruption, from 1st January, 1862,`
  line `to 1st January, 1882. The plaintiff is entitled to judgment.`
  line
  line `(b) In a like suit the plaintiff shows that the right was peaceably and openly enjoyed by him for`
  line `twenty years. The defendant proves that for a year of that time the plaintiff was entitled to possession`
  line `of the servient heritage as lessee thereof and enjoyed the right as such lessee. The suit shall be`
  line `dismissed, for the right of way has not been enjoyed "as an easement" for twenty years.`
  line
  line `(c) In a like suit the plaintiff shows that the right was peaceably and openly enjoyed by him for`
  line `twenty years. The defendant proves that the plaintiff on one occasion during the twenty years had`
  line `admitted that the user was not of right and asked his leave to enjoyed the right. The suit shall be`
  line `dismissed, for the right of way has not been enjoyed "as of rightd" for twenty years.`
obj_root_law_sections_15_footnotes:
  string
  line `1. Subs. by the A.O. 1950, for "Crown".`
  line
  line `2. Subs. by Act 36 of 1963, s. 28, for "sixty years" (w.e.f. 1-1-1964).`
obj_root_law_sections_16:
  sectionId (43952)
  sectionNo (16)
  orderNo 16
  title `Exclusion in favour of reversioner of servient heritage.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_16_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43952&sectionno=16&orderno=16&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_16_content:
  string
  line `Provided that, when any`
  line `land upon, over or from which any easement has been enjoyed or derived has been held under`
  line `or by virtue of any interest for life or any term of years exceeding three years from the`
  line `granting thereof, the time of the enjoyment of such easement during the continuance of such`
  line `interest or term shall be excluded in the computation of the said last-mentioned period of`
  line `twenty years, in case the claim is, within three years next after the determination of such`
  line `interest or term, resisted by the person entitled, on such determination, to the said land.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A sues for a declaration that he is entitled to a right of way over B's land. A proves that he has`
  line `enjoyed the right for twenty-five years; but B shows that during ten of these years C had a life-interest`
  line `in the land; that on C's death B became entitled to the land; and that within two years after C's death he`
  line `contested As claim to the right. The suit must he dismissed, as A, with reference to the provisions of`
  line `this section, has only proved enjoyment for fifteen years.`
obj_root_law_sections_16_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_17:
  sectionId (43953)
  sectionNo (17)
  orderNo 17
  title `Rights which cannot be acquired by prescription.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_17_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43953&sectionno=17&orderno=17&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_17_content:
  string
  line `Easements acquired under`
  line `section 15 are said to be acquired by prescription, and are called prescriptive rights.`
  line `None of the following rights can be so acquired:--`
  line
  line `(a) a right which would tend to the total destruction of the subject of the right, or the`
  line `property on which, if the acquisition were made, liability would be imposed;`
  line
  line `(b) a right to the free passage of light or air to an open space of ground;`
  line
  line `(c) a right to surface-water not flowing in a stream and not permanently collected in a`
  line `pool, tank or otherwise;`
  line
  line `(d) a right to underground water not passing in a defined channel.`
obj_root_law_sections_17_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_18:
  sectionId (43954)
  sectionNo (18)
  orderNo 18
  title `Customary easements.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_18_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43954&sectionno=18&orderno=18&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_18_content:
  string
  line `An easement may be acquired in virtue of a local custom.`
  line `Such easements are called customary easements.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) By the custom of a certain village every cultivator of village land is entitled, as such, to graze`
  line `his cattle on the common pasture. A having become the tenant of a plot of uncultivated land in the`
  line `village breaks up and cultivates that plot. He thereby acquires an easement to graze his cattle in`
  line `accordance with the custom.`
  line
  line `(b) By the custom of a certain town no owner or occupier of a house can open a new window`
  line `therein so as substantially to invade his neighbour's privacy. A builds a house in the town near B's`
  line `house. A thereupon acquires an easement that B shall not open new windows in his house so as to`
  line `command a view of the portions of A's house which are ordinarily excluded from observation, and B`
  line `acquires a like easement with respect to A's house.`
obj_root_law_sections_18_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_19:
  sectionId (43955)
  sectionNo (19)
  orderNo 19
  title `Transfer of dominant heritage passes easement.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_19_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_19_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43955&sectionno=19&orderno=19&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_19_content:
  string
  line `Where the dominant heritage is`
  line `transferred or devolves, by act of parties or by operation of law, the transfer or devolution`
  line `shall, unless a contrary intention appears, be deemed to pass the easement to the person in`
  line `whose favour the transfer or devolution takes place.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A has certain land to which a right of way is annexed. A lets the land to B for twenty years. The right of way`
  line `vests in B and his legal representative so long as the lease continues.`
obj_root_law_sections_19_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_20:
  sectionId (43956)
  sectionNo (20)
  orderNo 20
  title `Rules controlled by contract or title.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_20_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_20_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43956&sectionno=20&orderno=20&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_20_content:
  string
  line `The rules contained in this Chapter are controlled by`
  line `any contract between the dominant and servient owners relating to the servient heritage, and by the`
  line `provisions of the instrument or decree, if any, by which the easement referred to was imposed.`
  line
  line `Incidents of customary easements.--And when any incident of any customary easement is`
  line `inconsistent with such rules, nothing in this Chapter shall affect such incident.`
obj_root_law_sections_20_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_21:
  sectionId (43957)
  sectionNo (21)
  orderNo 21
  title `Bar to use unconnected with enjoyment.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_21_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_21_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43957&sectionno=21&orderno=21&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_21_content:
  string
  line `An easement must not be used for any purpose`
  line `not connected with the enjoyment of the dominant heritage.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A, as owner of a farm Y, has a right of way over B’s land to Y. Lying beyond Y, A has another farm Z,`
  line `the beneficial enjoyment of which is not necessary for the beneficial enjoyment of Y. He must not use the`
  line `easement for the purpose of passing to and from Z.`
  line
  line `(b) A, as owner of a certain house, has a right of way to and from it. For the purpose of passing to and from`
  line `the house, the right may be used, not only by A, but by the members of his family, his guests, lodgers, servants,`
  line `workmen, visitors and customers; for this is a purpose connected with the enjoyment of the dominant heritage.`
  line `So, if A lets the house, he may use the right of way for the purpose of collecting the rent and seeing that the`
  line `house is kept in repair.`
obj_root_law_sections_21_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_22:
  sectionId (43958)
  sectionNo (22)
  orderNo 22
  title `Exercise of ease dent. Confinement of exercise of easement.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_22_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_22_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43958&sectionno=22&orderno=22&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_22_content:
  string
  line `The dominant owner must`
  line `exercise his right in the mode which is least onerous to the servient owner; and, when the exercise of`
  line `an easement can without detriment to the dominant owner be confined to a determinate part of the`
  line `servient heritage, such exercise shall, at the request of the servient owner, be so confined.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A has a right of way over B's field. A must enter the way at either end and not at any intermediate point.`
  line
  line `(b) A has a right annexed to his house to cut thatching-grass in B's swamp. A, when exercising his easement,`
  line `must cut the grass so that the plants may not be destroyed.`
obj_root_law_sections_22_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_23:
  sectionId (43959)
  sectionNo (23)
  orderNo 23
  title `Right to alter mode of enjoyment.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_23_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_23_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43959&sectionno=23&orderno=23&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_23_content:
  string
  line `Subject to the provisions of section 22, the dominant`
  line `owner may, from time to time, alter the mode and place of enjoying the easement, provided that he`
  line `does not thereby impose any additional burden on the servient heritage.`
  line
  line `Exception.—The dominant owner of a right of way cannot vary his line of passage at pleasure,`
  line `even though he does not thereby impose any additional burden on the servient heritage.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A, the owner of a saw-mill, has a right to a flow of water sufficient to work the mill. He may convert the`
  line `saw mill into a corn-mill, provided that it can be worked by the same amount of water.`
  line
  line `(b) A has a right to discharge on B’s land the rain-water from the eaves of A’s house. This does not entitle A`
  line `to advance his eaves if, by so doing, he imposes a greater burden on B’s land.`
  line
  line `(c) A, as the owner of a paper-mill, acquires a right to pollute a stream by pouring in the refuse-liquor`
  line `produced by making in the mill paper from rags. He may pollute the stream by pouring in similar liquor`
  line `produced by making in the mill paper by a new process from bamboos, provided that he does not substantially`
  line `increase the amount, or injuriously change the nature, of the pollution.`
  line
  line `(d) A, a riparian owner, acquires, as against the lower riparian owners, a prescriptive right to pollute a stream`
  line `by throwing sawdust into it. This does not entitle A to pollute the stream by discharging into it poisonous liquor.`
obj_root_law_sections_23_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_24:
  sectionId (43960)
  sectionNo (24)
  orderNo 24
  title `Right to do acts to secure enjoyment.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_24_content
  footnotes `1. But see s. 36, infra, as to abatement of obstruction of easement.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43960&sectionno=24&orderno=24&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_24_content:
  string
  line `The dominant owner is entitled^1`
  line `, as against servient`
  line `owner, to do all acts necessary to secure the full enjoyment of the easement; but such acts must be`
  line `done at such time and in such manner as, without detriment to the dominant owner, to cause the`
  line `servient owner as little inconvenience as possible; and the dominant owner must repair, as far as`
  line `practicable, the damage (if any) caused by the act to the servient heritage.`
  line
  line `Accessory rights.--Rights to do acts necessary to secure the full enjoyment of an easement are`
  line `called accessory rights.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A has an easement to lay pipes in B’s land to convey water to A’s cistern. A may enter and dig the land`
  line `in order to mend the pipes, but he must restore the surface to its original state.`
  line
  line `(b) A has an easement of a drain through B's land. The sewer with which the drain communicates is altered.`
  line `A may enter upon B’s land and alter the drain, to adapt it to the new sewer, provided that he does not thereby`
  line `impose any additional burden on B's land.`
  line
  line `(c) A, as owner of a certain house, has a right of way over B's land. The way is out of repair, or a tree is`
  line `blown down and falls across it. A may enter on B's land and repair the way or remove the tree from it.`
  line
  line `(d) A, as owner of a certain field, has a right of way over B's land. B renders the way impassable. A may`
  line `deviate from the way and pass over the adjoining land of B, provided that the deviation is reasonable.`
  line
  line `(e) A, as owner of a certain house, has a right of way over B's field. A may remove rocks to make the way.`
  line
  line `(f) A has an easement of support from '’s wall. The wall gives way. A may enter upon B’s land and repair`
  line `the wall.`
  line
  line `(g) A has an easement to have his land flooded by means of a dam in B's stream. The dam is half swept`
  line `away by an inundation. A may enter upon B’s land and repair the dam.`
obj_root_law_sections_25:
  sectionId (43961)
  sectionNo (25)
  orderNo 25
  title `Liability for expenses necessary for preservation of easement.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_25_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_25_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43961&sectionno=25&orderno=25&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_25_content:
  string
  line `The expenses incurred in`
  line `constructing works, or making repairs, or doing any other act necessary for the use or preservation of`
  line `an easement, must be defrayed by the dominant owner.`
obj_root_law_sections_25_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_26:
  sectionId (43962)
  sectionNo (26)
  orderNo 26
  title `Liability for damage from want of repair.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_26_content
  footnotes `1. But see s. 50, infra, as to extinguishment or suspension of easement.`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43962&sectionno=26&orderno=26&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_26_content:
  string
  line `Where an easement is enjoyed by means of an`
  line `artificial work, the dominant owner is liable to make compensation for any damage to the servient`
  line `heritage arising from the want of repair of such work.^2`
obj_root_law_sections_27:
  sectionId (43963)
  sectionNo (27)
  orderNo 27
  title `Servient owner not bound to do anything.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_27_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_27_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43963&sectionno=27&orderno=27&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_27_content:
  string
  line `The servient owner is not bound to do anything`
  line `for the benefit of the dominant heritage, and he is entitled, as against the dominant owner, to use the`
  line `servient heritage in any way consistent with the enjoyment of the easement; but he must not do any`
  line `act tending to restrict the easement or to render its exercise less convenient.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A, as owner of a house, has a right to lead water and send sewage through B's land. B is not bound, as servient`
  line `owner, to clear the watercourse or scour the sewer.`
  line
  line `(b) A grants a right of way through his land to B as owner of a field. A may feed his cattle on grass growing on the way,`
  line `provided that B's right of way is not thereby obstructed; but he must not build a wall at the end of his land so as to prevent B`
  line `from going beyond it, nor must he narrow the way so as to render the exercise of the right less easy than it was at the date of`
  line `the grant.`
  line
  line `(c) A, in respect of his house, is entitled to an easement of support from B's wall. B is not bound, as servient owner, to`
  line `keep the wall standing and in repair. But he must not pull down or weaken the wall so as to make it incapable of rendering`
  line `the necessary support.`
  line
  line `(d) A, in respect of his mill, is entitled to a watercourse through B's land. B must not drive stakes so as to obstruct the`
  line watercourse.
  line
  line `(e) A, in respect of his house, is entitled to a certain quantity of light passing over B’s land. B must not plant trees so as`
  line `to obstruct the passage to A's windows of that quantity of light.`
obj_root_law_sections_27_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_28:
  sectionId (43964)
  sectionNo (28)
  orderNo 28
  title `Extent of easements.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_28_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_28_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43964&sectionno=28&orderno=28&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_28_content:
  string
  line `With respect to the extent of easements and the mode of their`
  line `enjoyment, the following provisions shall take effect:--`
  line
  line `Easement of necessity.--An easement of necessity is co-extensive with the necessity as it existed`
  line `when the easement was imposed.`
  line
  line `Other easements.--The extent of any other easement and the mode of its enjoyment must be`
  line `fixed with reference to the probable intention of the parties and the purpose for which the right was`
  line `imposed or acquired.`
  line
  line `In the absence of evidence as to such intention and purpose--`
  line
  line `(a) Right of way.--A right of way of any one kind does not include a right of way of any other`
  line kind;
  line `(b) Right to light or air acquired by grant.--The extent of a right to the passage of light or`
  line `air to a certain window, door or other opening, imposed by a testamentary or non-testamentary`
  line `instrument, is the quantity of light or air that entered the opening at the time the testator died or the`
  line `non-testamentary instrument was made;`
  line
  line `(c) Prescriptive right to light or air.--The extent of a prescriptive right to the passage of light`
  line `or air to a certain window, door or other opening is that quantity of light or air which has been`
  line `accustomed to enter that opening during the whole of the prescriptive period irrespectively of the`
  line `purposes for which it has been used;`
  line
  line `(d) Prescriptive right to pollute air or water.--The extent of a prescriptive right to pollute air`
  line `or water is the extent of the pollution at the commencement of the period of user on completion of`
  line `which the right arose; and`
  line
  line `(e) Other prescriptive rights.--The extent of every other prescriptive right and the mode of its`
  line `enjoyment must be determined by the accustomed user of the right.`
obj_root_law_sections_28_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_29:
  sectionId (43965)
  sectionNo (29)
  orderNo 29
  title `Increase of easement.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_29_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_29_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43965&sectionno=29&orderno=29&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_29_content:
  string
  line `The dominant owner cannot, by merely altering or adding to the`
  line `dominant heritage, substantially increase an easement.`
  line `Where an easement has been granted or bequeathed so that its extent shall be proportionate to the`
  line `extent of the dominant heritage, if the dominant heritage is increased by alluvion, the easement is`
  line `proportionately increased, and, if the dominant heritage is diminished by dilluvion, the easement is`
  line `proportionately diminished.`
  line
  line `Save as aforesaid, no easement is affected by any change in the extent of the dominant or the`
  line `servient heritage.`
  line
  line Illustrations/br
  line
  line `(a) A, the owner of a mill, has acquired a prescriptive right to divert to his mill part of the water of a stream.`
  line `A alters the machinery of his mill. He cannot therbey increase his right to divert water.`
  line
  line `(b) A has acquired an easement to pollute a stream by carrying on a manufacture on its banks by which a`
  line `certain quantity of foul matter is discharged into it. A extends his works and thereby increases the quantity`
  line `discharged. He is responsible to the lower riparian owners for injury done by such increase.`
  line
  line `(c) A, as the owner of a farm, has a right to take, for the purpose of manuring his farm, leaves which have`
  line `fallen from the trees on B’s land. A buys a field and unites it to his farm. A is not thereby entitled to take leaves`
  line `to manure this field.`
obj_root_law_sections_29_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_30:
  sectionId (43966)
  sectionNo (30)
  orderNo 30
  title `Partition of dominant heritage.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_30_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_30_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43966&sectionno=30&orderno=30&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_30_content:
  string
  line `Where a dominant heritage is divided between two or`
  line `more persons, the easement becomes annexed to each of the shares, but not so as to increase`
  line `substantially the burden on the servient heritage: Provided that such annexation is`
  line `consistent with the terms of the instrument, decree or revenue-proceeding (if any) under which the`
  line `division was made, and, in the case of prescriptive rights, with the user during the prescriptive period.`
  line
  line Illustrations
  line
  line `(a) A house to which a right of way by a particular path is annexed is divided into two parts, one of which is`
  line `granted to A, the other to B. Each is entitled, in respect of his part, to a right of way by the same path.`
  line
  line `(b) A house to which is annexed the right of drawing water from a well to the extent of fifty buckets a day is`
  line `divided into two distinct heritages, one of which is granted to A, the other to B. A and B are each entitled, in`
  line `respect of his heritage, to draw from the well fifty buckets a day; but the amount drawn by both must not exceed`
  line `fifty buckets a day.`
  line
  line `(c) A, having in respect of his house an easement of light, divides the house into three distinct heritages.`
  line `Each of these continues to have the right to have its windows unobstructed.`
obj_root_law_sections_30_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_31:
  sectionId (43967)
  sectionNo (31)
  orderNo 31
  title `Obstruction in case of excessive user.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_31_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_31_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43967&sectionno=31&orderno=31&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_31_content:
  string
  line `In the case of excessive user of an easement the`
  line `servient owner may, without prejudice to any other remedies to which he may be entitled, obstruct the`
  line `user, but only on the servient heritage: Provided that such user cannot be obstructed when the`
  line `obstruction would interfere with the lawful enjoyment of the easement.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A, having a right to the free passage over B's land of light to four windows six feet by four, increases their`
  line `size and number. It is impossible to obstruct the passage of light to the new windows without also obstructing`
  line `the passage of light to the ancient windows. B cannot obstruct the excessive user.`
obj_root_law_sections_31_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_32:
  sectionId (43968)
  sectionNo (32)
  orderNo 32
  title `Right to enjoyment without disturbance.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_32_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_32_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43968&sectionno=32&orderno=32&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_32_content:
  string
  line `The owner or occupier of the dominant heritage`
  line `is entitled to enjoy the easement without disturbance by any other person.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A, as owner of a house, has a right of way over B’s land. C unlawfully enters on B’s land, and obstructs A in`
  line `his right of way. A may sue C for compensation, not for the entry, but for the obstruction.`
obj_root_law_sections_32_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_33:
  sectionId (43969)
  sectionNo (33)
  orderNo 33
  title `Suit for disturbance of easement.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_33_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_33_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43969&sectionno=33&orderno=33&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_33_content:
  string
  line `The owner of any interest in the dominant heritage, or the`
  line `occupier of such heritage, may institute a suit for compensation for the disturbance of the easement or`
  line `of any right accessory thereto; provided that the disturbance has actually caused substantial damage to`
  line `the plaintiff.`
  line
  line `Explanation I.--The doing of any act likely to injure the plaintiff by affecting the evidence of the`
  line `easement, or by materially diminishing the value of the dominant heritage, is substantial damage`
  line `within the meaning of this section and section 34.`
  line
  line `Explanation II.--Where the easement disturbed is a right to the free passage of light passing to the`
  line `openings in a house, no damage is substantial within the meaning of this section unless it falls within`
  line `the first Explanation, or interferes materially with the physical comfort of the plaintiff, or prevents`
  line `him from carrying on his accustomed business in the dominant heritage as beneficially as he had done`
  line `previous to instituting the suit.`
  line
  line `Explanation III.--Where the easement disturbed is a right to the free passage of air to the openings`
  line `in a house, damage is substantial within the meaning of this section if it interferes materially with the`
  line `physical comfort of the plaintiff, though it is not injurious to his health.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `(a) A places a permanent obstruction in a path over which B, as tenant of C's house, has a right of way. This`
  line `is substantial damage to C, for it may affect the evidence of his reversionary right to the easement.`
  line
  line `(b) A, as owner of a house, has a right to walk along one side of B’'s house. B builds a verandah overhanging`
  line `the way about ten feet from the ground, and so as not to occasion any inconvenience to foot-passengers using`
  line `the way. This is not substantial damage to A.`
obj_root_law_sections_33_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_34:
  sectionId (43970)
  sectionNo (34)
  orderNo 34
  title `When cause of action arises for removal of support.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_34_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_34_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43970&sectionno=34&orderno=34&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_34_content:
  string
  line `The removal of the means of support to`
  line `which a dominant owner is entitled does not give rise to a right to recover compensation unless and until`
  line `substantial damage is actually sustained.`
obj_root_law_sections_34_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_35:
  sectionId (43971)
  sectionNo (35)
  orderNo 35
  title `Injunction to restrain disturbance.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_35_content
  footnotes `1. Ref. by Act 47 of 1963, s. 44 (w.e.f. 1-3-1964).`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43971&sectionno=35&orderno=35&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_35_content:
  string
  line `Subject to the provisions of the Specific Relief Act,`
  line 1877^1
  line `(1 of 1877), sections 52 to 57 (both inclusive), an injunction may be granted to restrain the`
  line `disturbance of an easement--`
  line
  line `(a) if the easement is actually disturbed--when compensation for such disturbance might be`
  line `recovered under this Chapter;`
  line
  line `(b) if the disturbance is only threatened or intended--when the act threatened or intended must`
  line `necessarily, if performed, disturb the easement.`
obj_root_law_sections_36:
  sectionId (43972)
  sectionNo (36)
  orderNo 36
  title `Abatement of obstruction of easement.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_36_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_36_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43972&sectionno=36&orderno=36&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_36_content:
  string
  line `Notwithstanding the provisions of section 24, the`
  line `dominant owner cannot himself abate a wrongful obstruction of an easement.`
obj_root_law_sections_36_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_37:
  sectionId (43973)
  sectionNo (37)
  orderNo 37
  title `Extinction by dissolution of right of servient owner.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_37_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_37_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43973&sectionno=37&orderno=37&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_37_content:
  string
  line `When, from a cause which preceded`
  line `the imposition of an easement, the person by whom it was imposed ceases to have any right in the`
  line `servient heritage, the easement is extinguished.`
  line
  line `Exception.--Nothing in this section applies to an easement lawfully imposed by a mortgagor in`
  line `accordance with section 10.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `(a) A transfers Sultanpur to B on condition that he does not marry C. B imposes an easement on Sultanpur.`
  line `Then B marries C. B’s interest in Sultanpur ends, and with it the easement is extinguished.`
  line
  line `(b) A, in 1860, let Sultanpur to B for thirty years from the date of the lease. B, in 1861, imposes an easement`
  line `on the land in favour of C, who enjoys the easement peaceably and openly as an easement without interruption`
  line `for twenty-nine years. B's interest in Sultanpur then ends, and with it C's easement.`
  line
  line `(c) A and B, tenants of C, have permanent transferable interests in their respective holdings. A imposes on`
  line `his holding an easement to draw water from a tank for the purpose of irrigating B’s land. B enjoys the easement`
  line `for twenty years. Then A's rent falls into arrear and his interest is sold. Bs easement is extinguished.`
  line
  line `(d) A mortgages Sultanpur to B, and lawfully imposes an easement on the land in favour of C in accordance`
  line `with the provisions of section 10. The land is sold to D in satisfaction of the mortgage-debt. The easement is not`
  line `thereby extinguished.`
obj_root_law_sections_37_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_38:
  sectionId (43974)
  sectionNo (38)
  orderNo 38
  title `Extinction by release.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_38_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_38_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43974&sectionno=38&orderno=38&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_38_content:
  string
  line `An easement is extinguished when the dominant owner releases it,`
  line `expressly or impliedly, to the servient owner.`
  line `Such release can be made only in the circumstances and to the extent in and to which the dominant`
  line `owner can alienate the dominant heritage.`
  line
  line `An easement may be released as to part only of the servient heritage.`
  line
  line `Explanation I.--An easement is impliedly released--`
  line
  line `(a) where the dominant owner expressly authorises an act of a permanent nature to be done on`
  line `the servient heritage, the necessary consequence of which is to prevent his future enjoyment of the`
  line `easement, and such act is done is pursuance of such authority;`
  line
  line `(b) where any permanent alteration is made in the dominant heritage of such a nature as to`
  line `show that the dominant owner intended to cease to enjoy the easement in future.`
  line
  line `Explanation II.--Mere non-user of an easement is not an implied release within the meaning of`
  line `this section.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `(a) A, B and C are co-owners of a house to which an easement is annexed. A, without the consent of B and`
  line `C, releases the easement. This release is effectual only as against A and his legal representative.`
  line
  line `(b) A grants B an easement over A’s land for the beneficial enjoyment of his house. B assigns the house to`
  line `C. B then purports to release the easement. The release is ineffectual.`
  line
  line `(c) A, having the right to discharge his eavesdroppings into B's yard, expressly authorises B to build over`
  line `this yard to a height which will interfere with the discharge. B builds accordingly. A's easement is extinguished`
  line `to the extent of the interference.`
  line
  line `(d) A, having an easement of light to a window, builds up that window with bricks and mortar so as to`
  line `manifest an intention to abandon the easement permanently. The easement is impliedly released.`
  line
  line `(e) A, having a projecting roof by means of which he enjoys an easement to discharge eavesdroppings on`
  line `B's land, permanently alters the roof so as to direct the rain-water into a different channel and discharge it on`
  line `C's land. The easement is impliedly released.`
obj_root_law_sections_38_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_39:
  sectionId (43975)
  sectionNo (39)
  orderNo 39
  title `Extinction by revocation.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_39_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_39_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43975&sectionno=39&orderno=39&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_39_content:
  string
  line `An easement is extinguished when the servient owner, in exercise`
  line `of a power reserved in this behalf, revokes the easement.`
obj_root_law_sections_39_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_40:
  sectionId (43976)
  sectionNo (40)
  orderNo 40
  title `Extinction on expiration of limited period or happening of dissolving condition.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_40_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_40_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43976&sectionno=40&orderno=40&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_40_content:
  string
  line An
  line `easement is extinguished where it has been imposed for a limited period, or acquired on condition that`
  line `it shall become void on the performance or non-performance of a specified act, and the period expires`
  line `or the condition is fulfilled.`
obj_root_law_sections_40_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_41:
  sectionId (43977)
  sectionNo (41)
  orderNo 41
  title `Extinction on termination of necessity.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_41_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_41_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43977&sectionno=41&orderno=41&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_41_content:
  string
  line `An easement is extinguished when it becomes incapable of`
  line `being at any time under any circumstances beneficial to the dominant owner.`
obj_root_law_sections_41_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_42:
  sectionId (43978)
  sectionNo (42)
  orderNo 42
  title `Extinction of useless easement.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_42_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_42_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43978&sectionno=42&orderno=42&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_42_content:
  string
  line `An easement is extinguished when it becomes incapable of`
  line `being at any time under any circumstances beneficial to the dominant owner.`
obj_root_law_sections_42_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_43:
  sectionId (43979)
  sectionNo (43)
  orderNo 43
  title `Extinction by permanent Change in dominant heritage.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_43_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_43_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43979&sectionno=43&orderno=43&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_43_content:
  string
  line `Where, by any permanent change`
  line `in the dominant heritage, the burden on the servient heritage is materially increased and cannot be`
  line `reduced by the servient owner without interfering with the lawful enjoyment of the easement, the`
  line `easement is extinguished, unless--`
  line
  line `(a) it was intended for the beneficial enjoyment of the dominant heritage, to whatever extent the`
  line `easement should be used; or`
  line
  line `(b) the injury caused to the servient owner by the change is so slight that no reasonable person`
  line `would complain of it; or`
  line
  line `(c) the easement is an easement of necessity.`
  line
  line `Nothing in this section shall be deemed to apply to an easement entitling the dominant owner to`
  line `support of the dominant heritage.`
obj_root_law_sections_43_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_44:
  sectionId (43980)
  sectionNo (44)
  orderNo 44
  title `Extinction on permanent alteration of servient heritage by superior force.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_44_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_44_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43980&sectionno=44&orderno=44&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_44_content:
  string
  line `An easement`
  line `is extinguished where the servient heritage is by superior force so permanently altered that the`
  line `dominent owner can no longer enjoy such easement:`
  line
  line `Provided that, where a way of necessity is destroyed by superior force, the dominant owner has a`
  line `right to another way over the servient heritage; and the provisions of section 14 apply to such way.`
  line /
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `(a) A grants to B, as the owner of a certain house, a right to fish in a river running through A's`
  line `land. The river changes its course permanently and runs through C's land. B's easement is`
  line extinguished.
  line
  line `(b) Access to a path over which A has a right of way is permanently cut off by an earthquake. A's`
  line `right is extinguished.`
obj_root_law_sections_44_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_45:
  sectionId (43981)
  sectionNo (45)
  orderNo 45
  title `Extinction by destruction of either heritage.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_45_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_45_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43981&sectionno=45&orderno=45&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_45_content:
  string
  line `An easement is extinguished when either the`
  line `dominant or the servient heritage is completely destroyed.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A has a right of way over a road running along the foot of a sea-cliff. The road is washed away by a`
  line `permanent encroachment of the sea. A’s easement is extinguished.`
obj_root_law_sections_45_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_46:
  sectionId (43982)
  sectionNo (46)
  orderNo 46
  title `Extinction by unity of ownership.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_46_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_46_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43982&sectionno=46&orderno=46&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_46_content:
  string
  line `An easement is extinguished when the same person`
  line `becomes entitled to the absolute ownership of the whole of the dominant and servient heritages.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `(a) A, as the owner of a house has a right of way over B’s field. A mortgages his house, and B mortgages his`
  line `field to C. Then C forecloses both mortgages and becomes thereby absolute owner of both house and field. The`
  line `right of way is extinguished.`
  line
  line `(b) The dominant owner acquires only part of the servient heritage: the easement is not extinguished, except`
  line `in the case illustrated in section 41.`
  line
  line `(c) The servient owner acquires the dominant heritage in connection with a third person: the easement is not`
  line extinguished.
  line
  line `(d) The separate owners of two separate dominant heritages jointly acquire the heritage which is servient to`
  line `the two separate heritages: the easements are not extinguished.`
  line
  line `(e) The joint owners of the dominant heritage jointly acquire the servient heritage: the easement is`
  line extinguished.
  line
  line `(f) A single right of way exists over two servient heritages for the beneficial enjoyment of a single dominant`
  line `heritage. The dominant owner acquires one only of the servient heritages. The easement is not extinguished.`
  line
  line `(g) A has a right of way over B’s road. B dedicates the road to the public. A’s right of way is not`
  line extinguished.
obj_root_law_sections_46_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_47:
  sectionId (43983)
  sectionNo (47)
  orderNo 47
  title `Extinction by non-enjoyment.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_47_content
  footnotes `1. See now the Registration Act, 1908 (16 of 1908).`
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43983&sectionno=47&orderno=47&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_47_content:
  string
  line `A continuous easement is extinguished when it totally ceases`
  line `to be enjoyed as such for an unbroken period of twenty years.`
  line
  line `A discontinuous easement is extinguished when, for a like period, it has not been enjoyed as such.`
  line
  line `Such period shall be reckoned, in the case of a continuous easement, from the day on which its`
  line `enjoyment was obstructed by the servient owner, or rendered impossible by the dominant owner; and,`
  line `in the case of a discontinuous easement, from the day on which it was last enjoyed by any person as`
  line `dominant owner:`
  line
  line `Provided that if, in the case of a discontinuous easement, the dominant owner, within such period,`
  line `registers, under the Indian Registration Act, 1877^1`
  line `(3 of 1877), a declaration of his intention to retain`
  line `such easement, it shall not be extinguished until a period of twenty years has elapsed from the date of`
  line `the registration.`
  line
  line `Where an easement can be legally enjoyed only at a certain place, or at certain times, or between`
  line `certain hours, or for a particular purpose, its enjoyment during the said period at another place, or at`
  line `other times, or between other hours, or for another purpose, does not prevent its extinction under this`
  line section.
  line
  line `The circumstance that, during the said period, no one was in possession of the servient heritage,`
  line `or that the easement could not be enjoyed, or that a right accessory thereto was`
  line `enjoyed, or that the dominant owner was not aware of its existence, or that he enjoyed it in ignorance`
  line `of his right to do so, does not prevent its extinction under this section.`
  line
  line `An easement is not extinguished under this section--`
  line
  line `(a) where the cessation is in pursuance of a contract between the dominant and servient owners;`
  line
  line `(b) where the dominant heritage is held in co-ownership, and one of the co-owners enjoys the`
  line `easement within the said period, or`
  line `(c) where the easement is a necessary easement.`
  line
  line `Where several heritages are respectively subject to rights of way for the benefit of a single`
  line `heritage, and the ways are continuous, such rights shall, for the purposes of this section, be deemed to`
  line `be a single easement.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A has, as annexed to his house, rights of way from the high road thither over the heritages X and Z and the intervening`
  line `heritage Y. Before the twenty years expire, A exercises his right of way over X. His rights of way over Y and Z are not`
  line extinguished.
obj_root_law_sections_48:
  sectionId (43984)
  sectionNo (48)
  orderNo 48
  title `Extinction of accessory rights.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_48_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_48_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43984&sectionno=48&orderno=48&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_48_content:
  string
  line `When an easement is extinguished, the rights (if any)`
  line `accessory thereto are also extinguished.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A has an easement to draw water from B's well. As accessory thereto, he has a right of way over B's land to`
  line `and from the well. The easement to draw water is extinguished under section 47. The right of way is also`
  line extinguished.
obj_root_law_sections_48_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_49:
  sectionId (43985)
  sectionNo (49)
  orderNo 49
  title `Suspension of easement.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_49_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_49_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43985&sectionno=49&orderno=49&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_49_content:
  string
  line `An easement is suspended when the dominant owner become`
  line `entitled to possession of the servient heritage for a limited interest therein, or when the servient owner`
  line `becomes entitled to possession of the dominant heritage for a limited interest therein.`
obj_root_law_sections_49_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_50:
  sectionId (43986)
  sectionNo (50)
  orderNo 50
  title `Servient owner not entitled to require continuance.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_50_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_50_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43986&sectionno=50&orderno=50&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_50_content:
  string
  line `The servient owner has no right to`
  line `require that an easement be continued; and, notwithstanding the provisions of section 26, he is not`
  line `entitled to compensation for damage caused to the servient heritage in consequence of the`
  line `extinguishment or suspension of the easement, if the dominant owner has given to the servient owner`
  line `such notice as will enable him, without unreasonable expense, to protect the servient heritage from`
  line `such damage.`
  line
  line `Compensation for damage caused by extinguishment or suspension.--Where such notice has`
  line `not been given, the servient owner is entitled to compensation for damage caused to the servient`
  line `heritage in consequence of such extinguishment or suspension.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A, in exercise of an easement, diverts to his canal the water of B's stream. The diversion continues for many years, and`
  line `during that time the bed of the stream partly fills up. A then abandons his easement, and restores the stream to its ancient`
  line `course. B's land is consequently flooded. B sues A for compensation for the damage caused by the flooding. It is proved that`
  line `A gave B a month’s notice of his intention to abandon the easement, and that such notice was sufficient to enable B, without`
  line `unreasonable expense, to have prevented the damage. The suit must he dismissed.`
obj_root_law_sections_50_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_51:
  sectionId (43987)
  sectionNo (51)
  orderNo 51
  title `Revival of easements.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_51_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_51_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43987&sectionno=51&orderno=51&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_51_content:
  string
  line `An easement extinguished under section 45 revives (a) when the`
  line `destroyed heritage is, before twenty years have expired, restored by the deposit of alluvion; (b) when`
  line `the destroyed heritage is a servient building and before twenty years have expired such building is`
  line `rebuilt upon the same site; and (c) when the destroyed heritage is a dominant building and before`
  line `twenty years have expired such building is rebuilt upon the same site and in such a manner as not to`
  line `impose a greater burden on the servient heritage.`
  line
  line `An easement extinguished under section 46 revives when the grant or bequest by which the unity of ownership was produced is set aside by the decree of a competent Court. A necessary`
  line `easement extinguished under the same section revives when the unity of ownership ceases from any`
  line `other cause.`
  line
  line `A suspended easement revives if the cause of suspension is removed before the right is`
  line `extinguished under section 47.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A, as the absolute owner of field Y, has a right of way thither over B’s field Z. A obtains from B a lease of Z`
  line `for twenty years. The easement is suspended so long as A remains lessee of Z. But when A assigns the lease to`
  line `C, or surrenders it to B, the right of way revives.`
obj_root_law_sections_51_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_52:
  sectionId (43988)
  sectionNo (52)
  orderNo 52
  title `"License" defined.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_52_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_52_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43988&sectionno=52&orderno=52&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_52_content:
  string
  line `Where one person grants to another, or to a definite number of other`
  line `persons, a right to do, or continue to do, in or upon the immovable property of the grantor, something`
  line `which would, in the absence of such right, be unlawful, and such right does not amount to an`
  line `easement or an interest in the property, the right is called a license.`
obj_root_law_sections_52_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_53:
  sectionId (43989)
  sectionNo (53)
  orderNo 53
  title `Who may grant license.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_53_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_53_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43989&sectionno=53&orderno=53&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_53_content:
  string
  line `A license may be granted by any one in the circumstances and to`
  line `the extent in and to which he may transfer his interests in the property affected by the license.`
obj_root_law_sections_53_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_54:
  sectionId (43990)
  sectionNo (54)
  orderNo 54
  title `Grant may be express or implied.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_54_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_54_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43990&sectionno=54&orderno=54&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_54_content:
  string
  line `The grant of a license may be express or implied from`
  line `the conduct of the grantor, and an agreement which purports to create an easement, but is ineffectual`
  line `for that purpose, may operate to create a license.`
obj_root_law_sections_54_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_55:
  sectionId (43991)
  sectionNo (55)
  orderNo 55
  title `Accessory licenses annexed by law.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_55_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_55_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43991&sectionno=55&orderno=55&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_55_content:
  string
  line `All licenses necessary for the enjoyment of any`
  line `interest, or the exercise of any right, are implied in the constitution of such interest or right. Such`
  line `licenses are called accessory licenses.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `A sells the trees growing on his land to B. B is entitled to go on the land and take away the trees.`
obj_root_law_sections_55_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_56:
  sectionId (43992)
  sectionNo (56)
  orderNo 56
  title `License when transferable.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_56_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_56_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43992&sectionno=56&orderno=56&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_56_content:
  string
  line `Unless a different intention is expressed or necessarily implied,`
  line `a license to attend a place of public entertainment may be transferred by the licensee; but, save as`
  line `aforesaid, a license cannot he transferred by the licensee or exercised by his servants or agents.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `(a) A grants B a right to walk over A’s field whenever he pleases. The right is not annexed to any`
  line `immovable property of B. The right cannot be transferred.`
  line
  line `(b) The Government grant B a license to erect and use temporary grain-sheds on Government land. In the`
  line `absence of express provision to the contrary, B’s servants may enter on the land for the purpose of erecting`
  line `sheds, erect the same, deposit grain therein and remove grain therefrom.`
obj_root_law_sections_56_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_57:
  sectionId (43993)
  sectionNo (57)
  orderNo 57
  title `Grantor's duty to disclose defects.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_57_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_57_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43993&sectionno=57&orderno=57&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_57_content:
  string
  line `The grantor of a license is bound to disclose to the`
  line `licensee any defect in the property affected by the license, likely to be dangerous to the person or`
  line `property of the licensee, of which the grantor is, and the licensee is not, aware.`
obj_root_law_sections_57_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_58:
  sectionId (43994)
  sectionNo (58)
  orderNo 58
  title `Grantor's duty not to render property unsafe.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_58_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_58_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43994&sectionno=58&orderno=58&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_58_content:
  string
  line `The grantor of a license is bound not to do`
  line `anything likely to render the property affected by the license dangerous to the person or property of`
  line `the licensee.`
obj_root_law_sections_58_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_59:
  sectionId (43995)
  sectionNo (59)
  orderNo 59
  title `Grantor's transferee not bound by license.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_59_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_59_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43995&sectionno=59&orderno=59&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_59_content:
  string
  line `When the grantor of the license transfers the`
  line `property affected thereby, the transferee is not as such bound by the license.`
obj_root_law_sections_59_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_60:
  sectionId (43996)
  sectionNo (60)
  orderNo 60
  title `License when revocable.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_60_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_60_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43996&sectionno=60&orderno=60&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_60_content:
  string
  line `A license may be revoked by the grantor, unless--`
  line
  line `(a) it is coupled with a transfer of property and such transfer is in force;`
  line
  line `(b) the licensee, acting upon the license, has executed a work of a permanent character and`
  line `incurred expenses in the execution.`
obj_root_law_sections_60_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_61:
  sectionId (43997)
  sectionNo (61)
  orderNo 61
  title `Revocation express or implied.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_61_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_61_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43997&sectionno=61&orderno=61&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_61_content:
  string
  line `The revocation of a license may be express or implied.`
  line
  line Illustration
  line
  line `(a) A, the owner of a field, grants a license to B to use a path across it. A, with intent to revoke the`
  line `license, locks a gate across the path. The license is revoked.br`
  line
  line `(b) A, the owner of a field, grants a license to B to stack hay on the field. A lets or sells the field to C.`
  line `The license is revoked.`
obj_root_law_sections_61_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_62:
  sectionId (43998)
  sectionNo (62)
  orderNo 62
  title `License when deemed revoked.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_62_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_62_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43998&sectionno=62&orderno=62&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_62_content:
  string
  line `A license is deemed to be revoked--`
  line
  line `(a) when, from a cause preceding the grant of it, the grantor ceases to have any interest in the`
  line `property affected by the license;`
  line
  line `(b) when the licensee releases it, expressly or impliedly, to the grantor or his representative;`
  line
  line `(c) where it has been granted for a limited period, or acquired on condition that it shall become`
  line `void on the performance or non-performance of a specified act, and the period expires, or the`
  line `condition is fulfilled;`
  line
  line `(d) where the property affected by the license is destroyed or by superior force so permanently`
  line `altered that the licensee can not longer exercise his right;`
  line
  line `(e) where the licensee becomes entitled to the absolute ownership of the property affected by`
  line `the license;`
  line
  line `(f) where the license is granted for a specified purpose and the purpose is attained, or`
  line `abandoned, or becomes impracticable;`
  line
  line `(g) where the license is granted to the licensee as holding a particular office, employment or`
  line `character, and such office, employment or character ceases to exist;`
  line
  line `(h) where the license totally ceases to be used as such for an unbroken period of twenty years,`
  line `and such cessation is not in pursuance of a contract between the grantor and the licensee;`
  line
  line `(i) in the case of an accessory license, when the interest or right to which it is accessory ceases`
  line `to exist.`
obj_root_law_sections_62_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_63:
  sectionId (43999)
  sectionNo (63)
  orderNo 63
  title `Licensee's rights on revocation.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_63_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_63_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=43999&sectionno=63&orderno=63&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_63_content:
  string
  line `Where a license is revoked, the licensee is entitled to a`
  line `reasonable time to leave the property affected thereby and to remove any goods which he has been`
  line `allowed to place on such property.`
obj_root_law_sections_63_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_sections_64:
  sectionId (44000)
  sectionNo (64)
  orderNo 64
  title `Licensee's rights on eviction.`
  content obj_root_law_sections_64_content
  footnotes obj_root_law_sections_64_footnotes
  query abv=CEN&statehandle=123456789/1362&actid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474&sectionId=44000&sectionno=64&orderno=64&orgactid=AC_CEN_3_20_00043_188205_1523272326474
obj_root_law_sections_64_content:
  string
  line `Where a license has been granted for a consideration, and the`
  line `licensee, without any fault of his own, is evicted by the grantor before he has fully enjoyed, under the`
  line `license, the right for which he contracted, he is entitled to recover compensation from the grantor.`
obj_root_law_sections_64_footnotes:
  string
  line
obj_root_law_translations:
  hi obj_root_law_translations_hi
